        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <date>Ap. 27</date>
                    <salute>My dear old George—</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am very very glad of your news about your attacking so difficult a problem with a strong hope of success.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I confess that I was alarmed when I heard that you c<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> not get the subject out of your head until I came to your last sentence that you w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> be careful.— Do not be too much disappointed if your idea breaks down. It seems a capital idea consulting Adams.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>I am sure some mathematical discussions will be valued greatly by geologists who thought tremendously &amp; it now appears overrated the value of Hopkins work about elevation.—<ref target="#foot.f4"/> There certainly have been enormous changes of level where our continents now stand, &amp; great subsidence in the Pacific. Most geologists now believe that continents have existed nearly where continents now are at all known times— I shall be very glad to help in expence of paid calculation.—<ref target="#foot.f5"/></p>
<p>My dear old f. | Your affect. Father | C. Darwin<ref target="#foot.f6"/></p>
<p>I have just been arranging for a <hi rend="underline">Spanish</hi> Translat of Origin!<ref target="#foot.f7"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">2.5 nearly] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10472.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from G. H. Darwin, 25 April 1876</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10472.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from G. H. Darwin, 25 April 1876</ref>; George was working on the problem of whether upheaval and subsidence of the continents influenced the position of the polar axis.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_30.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">John Couch Adams</ref>; see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10472.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from G. H. Darwin, 25 April 1876</ref> and n. 3.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2380.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Hopkins</ref> produced several papers on continental elevation, including <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_3844.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Hopkins 1836</ref>, which CD cited in his paper <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8002.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">‘Volcanic phenomena and the formation of mountain chains’</ref>, p. 624.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">In his letter of 25 April 1876, George had suggested employing people to do the mathematical calculations required for his paper (G. H. Darwin 1876b).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">This letter was written in pencil. Another person subsequently inked in the whole letter, except the salutation and part of the signature, in a fair imitation of CD’s hand.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f7"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6014.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref> 6d ed.; see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10481.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Enrique Godínez, 28 April 1876</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
